    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the issue is that the stack traces a bit too heavy for our current logging buffer, so I can't keep everything in memory. if i can't use a full instrumentation approach, are there other ways to narrow down which subsystems or specific objects are likely responsible for the creeping consumption? maybe something less intrusive than wrapping every single call?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the stack trace logging is too heavy, you'll need a more targeted, less intrusive approach, which is akin to a scavenger hunt for the most greedy components. You can't track every tiny bit of memory, but you can track the *growth* of specific pools.\n\nInstead of tracking *every* allocation, focus on tracking the *total allocated size* for specific subsystems or object types. For instance, if you have a subsystem managing sensor data buffers, add a counter to that subsystem's class that increments every time it allocates a buffer and decrements when it frees one. If the counter for that subsystem keeps climbing over time, you've found your leaky section, even if you don't know the exact line yet.\n\nYou could also use periodic heap profiling, if your RTOS or bare-metal environment allows for it. Periodically (say, every 10 minutes), take a snapshot of the heap usage. If the usage consistently increases between snapshots, you know *something* is leaking, and you can then narrow down which subsystem was most active during that interval.",
      "source": "target",
